The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", released a brochure
Women declared witches in Burkina Faso have several common features.
They belong to the older generation, can’t work for health reasons, are single and have no children.
The witch who becomes a witch is sent to isolation so as not to threaten the rest of the village.
“A man will rarely get this fate.”
"Young healthy women are also not removed because they help work and give birth to children," describes a regular nurse who, in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, cares in a special home of more than a hundred women whom their community has expelled from their ranks.
The local government has now decided to take action against the unusual “social measure.”
She published an information brochure to help curb the witch hunt.
It has a hook.
“More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso can’t read,” Die Standard.
Accusations of witchcraft are common in other African countries as well.
In Ghana, which is neighboring Burkina Faso, Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week after being tortured, poured petrol and burned by three women and two men.
This was by the BBC.
The perpetrators said it was an unfortunate coincidence of circumstances.
According to their version, the woman was inflamed with oil, which is used for ritual anointing.
It was said to have burned up after the group wanted to “destroy the evil spirit” from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is encouraged by people regardless of the level of education achieved.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: “The devouring of human souls has always been a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso, the government is trying to mitigate the witch hunt, in Gambia, the president himself participated in it last year.
“Gambia’s President Jammi, after his aunt’s death, launched a massive witch hunt, allegedly involved in her death and attempting to kill the president with black magic.”
“He called for help from shamans from nearby Guinea who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the president’s personal guard, forcibly drove randomly selected men and women from the Gambia villages to the president’s farm in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
In the farm, prisoners had to drink a drug from herbs with hallucinogenic effects, which also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
The two inmates did not survive on the farm.
Following international pressure, almost a thousand prisoners were eventually released.
