There is a school building, the architects know.
The administrative building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect it to also hide a mini-school with everything to it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, a bunch of toys, and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, children of Arch.Design employees can visit it.
The project and architectural company Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of important Brno buildings emerged, had been counting on space for its corporate mini-school from the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
It employs almost 90 people, mostly in the baby boom age, and it was important for women designers and architects to get back to work quickly.
Along with the possibility of reduced hours, the kindergarten is a benefit that Arch.Design offers its employees as part of the social program.
Architects and builders have the opportunity to combine a challenging job with caring for a child.
The mini-school was designed by the employees of Arch.Design and, with the support of the management, they managed to obtain a grant from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The project is financed by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to grant funding (subsidy of SEK 2.8 million) they were able to purchase equipment and equipment and for two years to ensure qualified personnel and operation.
Upon expiry of the financial subsidy (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to operate the mini-school for 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of the project took a year and Economy Rating helped significantly with the application for subsidy.
Care is provided by qualified staff, the children are cared for by a nurse and a teacher of MŠ, so children can go to the kindergarten without age restriction, but most of them are older than 3 years.
Because it is a "mini-school", only 5 children can be present at the same time, but more are replaced during the day.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten regardless of the hierarchy of position in the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the program filling in a mini-school is comparable to the framework program of preschool education.
Children not only play here, but they are also provided with quality teaching - from basic knowledge to preparation for school bays, English is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check their child at any time and stressful situations with delayed picking up children from kindergartens far from the workplace of their parents are eliminated.
Parents use their working hours more productively.
It is not surprising that there is a loyal employee-employee relationship.
Arch.Design has thus ranked among Czech companies that offer a significant benefit in recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and through this program strengthened personnel marketing.
A house of bones fascinates even after 100 years. Look into the interiors by Gaudí
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric donkey, the staircase resembles the dinosaur’s spine, and the balconies are open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló in Barcelona by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
From the locals, the house, thanks to its organic shapes, earned the nickname House of Bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, pieces of stoves and mosaics, a façade reminiscent of shells and ubiquitous soft curves, all of this is typical of Antoni Gaudí’s secession.
The facade of the house plays dreamy lines, gentle colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
When observed in detail, geometry, rhythm and a thoughtful order can be seen.
At night, the entire facade of the home sounds even more dramatic, it is illuminated so that the impression of the gloss of colors is further enhanced.
Forced and twisted shapes appear to the same extent in the interiors.
Wood in the waves copies window frames, fence, decorative elements of doors, cranes and bars.
The Batlló House, which stands in the Eixample district on the busy Passeig de Grácia No. 43, was created by the reconstruction of the 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the old building and building a completely new one, but soon accepted Gaudí’s idea for an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
Casa Batlló was not designed by Antoni Gaudí.
It was designed by architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his designer board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the use of mosaics on the facade were created.
A number of other artists and artists also worked on the facade.
The joint work on the designs of the Casa Batlló started the successful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá and the Park Güell, in which Gaudí's other works are located.
From the locals, the house soon after completion earned the nickname "House of Bones" thanks to its organic shapes.
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it the "sucking house".
It is also said that on the top of the building is depicted the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia.
Hidden religious motifs also contain other sculpture elements of the building.
Gaudí designed for his time a unique central heating system with ventilation springs and typical chimneys.
Strange may seem their forty-five degrees slope.
In Gaudí’s creation, he absolutely did not respect the construction regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be bound by them.
At the beginning of the construction, he obtained a building permit from the city, but the data on the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, when completing, the city council was overwhelmed by the result and requested rectification.
For example, the construction of the building interfered with the pillar and the public path.
The remedy never occurred, on the contrary: only fifteen days after the call of the municipality, Josep Batlló applied for (and successfully obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner moved to the lower floor.
The gallery on the second floor was a social lounge and on the third floor a bedroom and private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house is crossed by stairs, which can be taken up to the roof terrace itself.
The fundamental elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of interconnecting spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon door and the larger company can communicate comfortably without retaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
In addition to the new facade, the house with Gaudí's reconstruction has also received a non-traditional roofing and two additional floors.
Gaudí's play with light, blue and white glazed tiles, which cover the inner courtyard, and lights, is also impressive.
The game of two colors provides maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which absorbs sunlight.
Casa Batlló, which was listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2005, can be visited by anyone.
On the first floor of the building, the most spacious and spacious apartment is open to the public.
The owners decided for this move only in 2002, on the occasion of the celebration of the 150th anniversary of the famous creator's birth.
They persisted in the inspections, as they found that it was a very profitable business, and in addition, the inspections were expanded to include common and loft spaces, including a roof terrace.
The entrance fee to the monument is definitely not negligible, it is 16.50 euros and students, retirees, groups and holders of tourist cards have a 20% discount.
The amount is much more expensive than the entrance fee to Gaudi’s other buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the true atmosphere of the house with the dragon towers, you must quickly make friends with some of the inhabitants of the bar and visit him directly at home.
How to choose a mattress and a roof: women have different requirements than men
Not the honing frame of the bed, but the quality of the bed area, i.e. the mattress and the roof, give the basis for a really good bed.
However, they must be harmoniously supplemented in order to suit the specific user.
When choosing a lot of things decides, from the weight, height, age, health status and gender of the owner.
Also important is the type of interior in which the mattress and roof are purchased.
A typical example?
For example, for weekend chalets, where they are not regularly washed, latex mattresses are not suitable because they are "warming up" more slowly.
Moreover, they have a significantly higher weight than a standard polyurethane mattress.
It is necessary to turn them regularly.
If they do not have a lot of aeration channels in the core, and still lie on a solid plate, they retain moisture: mold could also appear underneath them.
The habit also determines the choice.
Anyone who has spent a long time abroad, where a lot of high mattresses with a softening layer are often used, will hardly feel good on a low and hard surface.
"Maybe all the hockey players who came back from the NHL complained to me that they would not sleep here."
"For their crumbling shoulders, heels and hips, they needed mattresses with a softening layer of lazy foam."
"Such ones are recommended for people with diabetes who have a disorder of the nervous system, so they get poorly "information" from joints and skin," explains Sylva Hadamczik, who specializes in carved furniture.
Many hockey players, but also other customers therefore years ago a mattress with lazy foam sought.
"Today it is cool, suitable mattresses have Tempur, Italian Magniflex, but also Czech Tropico."
You don’t have to be an NHL fighter to appreciate the lazy foam.
This “miracle” works simply.
It optimizes its stiffness and shape according to the absorbed heat or adjusts to your warm body.
Nothing pushes you, you won’t turn over at night like after a tough match.
You will sleep better.
The linen foam also acts as a protection against stains.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add the length of the foot to your height, which is about 21 to 34 cm.
Both men and women with a height of around 180 cm need a bed of 210 to 220 cm.
The minimum width for one should be 90 cm for a double bed, so together 180 cm.
For separate beds, such as singles, it is recommended to have at least 120 to 140 cm.
For convenience and possible visit.
"Otherwise, the rule for the width of the bed is simple: when lying on your back, you should have your hands comfortably slightly crumbled in the elbow," advises Ing. Helena Prokopová, the master of the Cechu of Carpenters and Decorators, who has been dedicated to the issue of healthy sleep and ergonomics of furniture for a number of years and lectures it at professional schools.
For a double bed, each needs its own roof and mattress, but be careful when buying to match the height of the mattress.
Otherwise, there will be nothing but to mount the roofs to different heights, but you may not succeed in each frame of the bed.
Foam mattresses should have a height of at least 14 cm, types with a sprinkle skeleton of at least 15, of which at least three centimeters should be counted on the shaping and brushing layer.
"When touching your hands or sitting on the mattress, you should definitely not feel the springs," warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a certain type of roof.
The whole bed, when the mattress and the base are like the grown Siamese twins, have nothing to do in the bedrooms.
The mattresses are poorly ventilated, they cannot be washed, which is already common today.
And since we usually sweat out 0.2 to 0.75 liters of sweat per night, it is clear that after five to seven years the mattress will start to resemble a large (and clogged) sitch.
Therefore, experts reject advertising slogans about the lifetime of mattresses up to 25 years, or even lifetime guarantees.
Everything has its ALE.
Therefore, advice from the practice of dealers: for mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, do not give up hygiene and work removable coating, but rather add a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Although mattresses are commonly manufactured throughout the perimeter, so after the breakup we get two parts (for washing and the size of the washing machine very important!), however, the manipulation of larger types (and one person) during the shooting may resemble a lightweight match in the ring with a heavy one.
Do you have a solid plate in your bed?
never ever !
Maximum for a bed intended for one night visits.
Nevertheless, provide the plate with (if it does not already have) ventilation holes and use a mattress with a sprinkle skeleton and a height of at least 15 cm with springs in bags (from it.Taschenfederkern) and a cyprus layer.
A polyurethane mattress does not belong to such a base.
The latex or sandwich mattresses (e.g. a combination of latex and coconut) will be suitable for non-logging lamel routes with 14 to 18 lamels, but you will always pay for routes with a greater number of lamels, 28 or more, where the lamels in the lobe area are doubled and their stiffness can be regulated.
A mattress with a sprinkle skeleton does not belong to the positioning lamel roof, because they do not respond to the positioning.
In addition to adjusting the rigidity of the lamels, you can also use the so-called shoulder collar.
It is a special attachment of the lamels, which allows you to press, or even tilt the lamel so that the shoulder of the sleeper is pretty "shut down".
For men who have “shoulders across the whole back”, it’s definitely an important thing.
Even the manufacturers of mattresses already remember it, who in the "man" began to use the softening zone precisely in the area of the shoulders.
They also remember women - they give them a softer surface in the hips.
For the most demanding customers are designed wing or plate roofs with so-called multitorz roofing.
The pressure disperses into several points and the tension decreases.
However, be careful, once you use the wrong pillow on the right mattress and roof (large and "blown"), most "plus" will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should support the head and the tips should only interfere with the shoulders so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
As a suitable size, 50 x 60 cm is recommended, which is preferred for example in Scandinavia.
When lying on the side, the pillow should align (together with the shoulder collar of the roof or the softened zone in the mattress) the height of the shoulder.
Modern mattresses have something in common with the original slugs filled with grass.
Their manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least compounds.
The trend is in the mattress as well.
Oil raw materials, from which polyurethane foams are made, are replaced with natural oils, for example, from shrimp and soybeans.
Soya is used by all known producers.
“Bio for mattresses means that the core is made of a material of purely natural origin,” explains Petr Vašíček from Tropico Plus.
Natural substances are also used in the manufacture of mattress coatings, one of the first was aloe vera.
You can also use micro-capsules to release the fresh smell of wood or lavender.
There is also a division for men and women.
While men are “cooled” by the vegetable extract from breeze so that the mattress can absorb heat and cool the body, women are instead “heated”.
Red pepper extract increases blood circulation, making it warmer for the weaker sex.
Favorite today?
A mattress made of cold foam (it has larger pores with a violated cellular structure, so it is more breathable than conventional polyurethane and offers better elasticity.
The combination of various rigidities of cold foams and "linny" foams creates multi-zone mattresses that know exactly where the head, hips and heels should be.
For a quality mattress you will pay from seven thousand crowns and above.
Those that meet health parameters, have a lower VAT rate, are taken as medical devices.
Gumotex was the first to this advantage in the Czech Republic.
Saving on mattress and roof is not easy.
Sometimes you can take advantage of the actions of manufacturers or sellers, who offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers a Duofreeze mattress with memory foam Memory in the coating for SEK 11,990.
