More and more parents want to monitor their children.
Fear of their own child is bringing more and more people to the idea of monitoring through GPS.
The system originally created for the search for cars can also track the movement of people, and thus help in such cases as the disappearance of the nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is so far as a box of sulphur, but soon it can only be as big as a watch.
Many people were frightened by the disappearance of Anička and began to search for ways to better protect their children.
At the expense of their privacy.
“We are trying to tell everyone that this is not spying, but another way to reduce the likelihood of a tragedy,” said Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking equipment to the Czech market.
“I admit that in some cases such devices can be misused, for example, when they are put in a bag to someone who doesn’t know about it, but we haven’t encountered such a case yet.”
“Most of the time, customers actually buy it for safety reasons,” Pilin added.
According to him, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how it is used in case of an emergency.
Children’s psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child doesn’t want to wear anything like this, he will simply get rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity in how to deliberately lose some things when they don't want to be under control."
"Great expectations were raised earlier in parents mobile phones, but they can be turned off just like these surveillance devices," Bočková says.
It is also controversial whether such a device would actually help in the event of an attack.
“When it comes to a prepared kidnapping, the perpetrator will almost always ensure that the child does not have any electronics with him that could reveal his location.”
“It’s a phone.”
“When surveillance devices begin to expand, they will search for them as well, because their sales will be supported by massive advertising.”
“In this case, criminals will always be one step ahead of the police,” says the psychologist.
However, he admits that a similar device can help in the event of a sudden pedophile attack.
According to Robert Chech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and persons, even if a tracking device is immediately destroyed after an attack, its presence can help.
"The device can be set to regularly send a location after a certain period of time."
"If it is damaged, at least the last location of the person concerned will be available."
"Dropper devices have built-in náklonometers, so even if a person just slipped and remained immovably lying, the device immediately sends a warning with a position," says Čech.
According to him, a similar service can also be performed by smart phones with navigation, where it is enough to upload special software.
The problem with current surveillance units is that they are either devices similar to the size of a syrup box or smaller mobile phones.
There is always a danger of loss.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, therefore, devices that look like a regular digital watch are now being tested.
"This will have the greatest advantage in the fact that a potential aggressor may not be able to recognize the tracking device at all."
"Or he will only recognize them after a while and that may give the police extra time," he adds.
Whether tracking devices evolve into bracelets or hooks, they will still use the same technology used to guard cars.
This is a combination of localization using GPS (which is used by conventional autonavigation) and a mobile phone function that reports the car’s current position.
