A longer index than a ring indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have an index ring longer than the ring are at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the conclusion of a study published on Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
It may be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, especially for men under 60,” said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Research on Cancer at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, especially in combination with genetic risk or other threatening factors, such as family health burden, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues in the UK followed more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and more than 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the index on their right hand shorter than the ring.
They had the same risk of developing prostate cancer as 19 percent of those with the same length of fingers.
For those who had the index ring longer than the ring, however, this risk decreased by 33 percent, compared to 87 percent for men up to the age of 60.
The length ratio of the two fingers – formed during the prenatal period – seems to reflect the different levels of the sex hormones to which the baby is exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer indicator.
Previous research has shown that testosterone contributes to the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, said that he knows about this study, but he does not think that the relationship between the length of the fingers and cancer would be "completely proven".
