The U.S. military has deployed a new "smart" weapon in Afghanistan, known so far only under the code name XM-25.
The generals hope that the new automatic rifle will affect the conflict with the Taliban and "change the game" in their favor.
The new weapon is something like a small super-precision gun.
The projectiles are powered by a laser with a precision of a few meters.
The special 25mm caliber bullets, developed for this rifle and containing highly explosive explosives, actually act like small grenades.
The bullets can be programmed to explode not only when they hit the target, but at any point in their ballistic path.
They can be used against an enemy who is hiding behind a barrier, behind a wall or in a dungeon.
He is usually not protected from above, and when a murderous rain of steel bars falls on him, it can bring him out of battle.
According to Richard Audett, who was involved in the development of the XM-25, the new rifle is the first infantry weapon that uses "smart" technology.
“A soldier treats it in principle by finding a target, sending a laser beam to determine the distance, obtaining a specified point of intent, adjusting the direction according to it and pressing the pipe.”
“Let’s say you measured 543 meters.”
"When you press the trigger, the gun charges and fires the missile to a distance of 543 meters plus minus one, two or three meters," Audette said.
