Support for democracy in Latin America is growing, as is support for private business.
Crime is worse than unemployment.
And many regions consider Brazil to be more influential than the United States.
These are some of the results of the recent Latinobarometer survey, conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in the journal The Economist.
Since the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it can trace changes in attitudes across the region.
This year’s survey, which took place in September and early October, dominates two related issues.
The first is that Latin America has a fairly cheerful mood.
The second is to increase the stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy in several countries on the outskirts of the Pacific in South America has increased significantly (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has been on average 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy was recovering after a deep decline in output last year.
But only about half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous regions, are believed Democrats, which pulls down the regional average (see Graph 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents across the region expressed satisfaction with how democracy works in practice in their country, the same number as last year, but compared to 2001, when it was 25%, it is a big increase (Chart 3).
Approximately 34% said they trust the parliament in their country and 45% trust the government, again the same numbers as last year, but this is a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, Latin America was undermined by the economic crisis.
Support was created during the global financial crisis probably because many Latin American countries suffered only a short recession and a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social security network has helped protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America announced this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and fell again to 32% this year.)
But the mood varies in a wide spectrum from country to country (see Graph 4).
Brazil’s strong economic performance and the popularity of its retired president, Luiza Inácio Lula da Silva, are reflected in the widely accepted sense of progress.
This situation is more rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more severe and the situation of violent crime has worsened.
Only for the second time since the polls began, more respondents across Latin America see crime as the most important problem rather than unemployment (see Graph 5).
Approximately 31% say they themselves or their close relatives were victims of crime last year, but this is a decrease from 38% last year and is also the lowest number since 1995.
More massive economic performance is reflected in increasing support for private business and a market economy: approximately 71% of respondents across the area say that private business is essential for development, this percentage increasing from 56% in 2007 (see Graph 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will enable the development of their country, this percentage increased from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have the same opinion (and 80% there support private business), although their leftist president Hugo Chavez expropriates many private companies.
Brazil is the country leading in the area, as mentioned by 19% of respondents (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, compared to unchanged last year) and Venezuela (9%, compared to 11% last year)
However, the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, with Venezuela enjoying success in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
