Grammy Awards: Michael Daugherty, Steve Mackey lead in classical music category
Nominations for classical music have a wide range of musicians and composers from around the world at the 53rd annual Grammy Awards.
The lead in the nomination is Michael Daugherty and his "Deus Ex Machina" for piano and orchestra, with five points, and Steve Mackey with his album "Dreamhouse", an eclectic orchestral work, with three points.
Among the nominees with links to Southern California appeared Estonian composer Arvo Pärt and his Symphony No. 4 "Los Angeles", a work that was ordered through the Los Angeles Philharmonic and debuted at the Walt Disney Concert Hall in 2009.
L.A. based composer Avner Dorman and his Mandolin Concerto also have a chance to be awarded.
Classical music nominations are divided into 13 categories, which include orchestral, opera, choir and solo recordings.
The classical music producer of the year category has five nominees, namely Blanton Alspaugh, David Frost, Tim Handley, Marina and Victor Ledin and James Mallinson.
Nominations for the classic album were won by Bruckner and his Symphony No. 3 and 4 from the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra; Daugherty and his "Deus Ex Machina" and "Metropolis Symphony" from the Nashville Symphony Orchestra; Steven Mackey and his "Dreamhouse" from the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Synergy Vocals; "Sacrificium - the Art of the Castrati" featuring various artists; and Verdi's "Requiem" from the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and Chorus.
As for the opera category, the nominees are Berg and "Lulu" from the Orchestra of the Royal Opera House; Adolf Hasse and "Marc Antonio e Cleopatra" from Ars Lyrica Houston; Kaija Saaria and "L'Amour de Loin" from the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin; Rodion Shchedrin and "The Enchanted Wanderer" from the Orchestra and Chorus of the Mariinsky Theatre; and Arthur Sullivan and "Ivanhoe" from the BBC National Orchestra of Wales.
Among the Grammy nominees for contemporary songs are Pärt for Symphony No. 4, Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina", Hans Werner Henze for "Appassionatamente Plus", Magnus Lindberg for "Graffiti" and Shchedrin for "The Enchanted Wanderer."
Pärt's Symphony No. 4 premiered at Disney Hall in January 2009 at a performance recorded by the L.A. Philharmonic under Esa-Pekko Salonena.
The 30-minute piece is called “Los Angeles” and is dedicated to former oil magnate Mikhail Khodorkovsky, who is imprisoned in Russia.
Dorman and "Mandolin Concerto" was nominated for instrumental performances by a soloist with an orchestra.
The L.A. composer said he wrote a 15-minute work specifically for mandolin artist Avi Avitala, who performed at a concert with the New York-based Metropolis Ensemble.
"I wrote it with the help of tones from the Middle East and many North African rhythms," Dorman said in a telephone conversation.
Dirigent Pierre Boulez, 85, received a nomination in the category for orchestral performance, for leading the Chicago Symphony in recording the works of Stravinsky.
The instrumental soloists nominated include pianists Nelson Freire and Marc-André Hamelin; organist Paul Jacobs; violinist Julia Fischer; and harpist Sarah Schuster Ericsson.
Among the nominated vocal soloists this year only women were represented, namely Anne Sofie Von Otter, Cecilia Bartoli, Lucia Duchon, Vivica Genaux and Measha Brueggergosman.
In the classical transition category, sopranist Jessie Norman won the nomination for her record "Roots - My Life, My Song."
