Microbes with resistance to arsenic increase the possibility of new types of life on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the space for the search for new forms of life on Earth and possibly beyond.
Researchers have discovered an unusual bacterium here on Earth and claim it is a sign that life has options that stand beyond the main elements that have been considered so far and fundamental.
“This body has a double capacity.”
"It can grow either thanks to phosphorus or arsenic."
“This fact is very strange, but it’s not proof that it’s a form of truly ‘extraterrestrial’ life,” said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report, which appeared on Thursday in the online issue of Science.
For a long time it has been considered necessary for life six main elements - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, scientists have found that bacteria discovered in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue to grow after phosphorus is replaced with arsenic.
“You’ll start to be surprised at what’s still possible,” said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
This finding is significant for the search for life outside of Earth, as researchers must be able to recognize life and know how life might look, Anbar said.
The study focuses on microbes found on Earth.
However, a report about this newcomer published to discuss it, which did not disclose the details of the finding, sparked widespread speculation on the Internet that the report reveals the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
is not so.
The discovery “shows that other planetary organisms may be able to take advantage of other elements that drive biochemistry and that a set of elements that we consider ‘standard’ may not be so absolutely necessary for life,” explained Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows the replacement of one element with another element in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It was not a coincidental finding.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the Astrobiology Institute at NASA, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it shows high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so it was considered that a microbe exposed to both elements could be able to replace one by another.
“Arsenic is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus.”
“As a result, it is very difficult for organisms to separate these elements from each other.”
"H, arsenic is so different that it doesn't work like phosphorus.When it gets into the body, it starts working in biochemical processes," Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to rising concentrations of arsenic, which are bacteria capable of adapting and growing.
Microbes grow better under the action of phosphorus, but since they can survive with arsenic replacement, there is an increased chance that life forms that use arsenic may occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, stated that the idea of arsenic replacing phosphorus is not new, but there has never been an example to prove this fact.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, so scientists speculated that it could have been used by earlier forms of life.
"This suggests that there could have been other ways to create life, not just the way it formed in the early Earth period," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simons research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
