How to interpret these movements?
It should be said in advance that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, this is another point in the complex process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future is to be, colliding with the idea of adhering to the old traditions that a large part of the other members hold.
Faced with European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong eurozone, which would include Germany, but also Austria and the Netherlands, for example, while the southern countries would leave the eurozone.
The second is a return to March – although now it may seem like science fiction, this version has widespread support from the public, approaching 50% of the population.
The third option, according to the German proposals, is the revision of the euro with greater macroeconomic supervision, budgetary tightening, fines for the guilty states, possible deferral of payments for some of them, and the extension of possible regulatory costs to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time, so there is now no room for quotes.
First, when both the International Monetary Fund and the European Commission encouraged deficits in 2009, the German government pulled a constitutional reform out of its sleeve to prevent them from starting in 2016.
This was the first sign of a contradiction between what Germany considered right (the plans for fiscal tightening and the stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including France, practiced.
The second was shown by this Central European country as Merkel painfully delayed the decision to save Greece.
It was already the subject of sharp criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and the public opinion, which was also published, were strongly against saving Greece.
Finally, in the last few days of October, Merkel has again appeared with a clear position when she called for the reform of the European Union treaties so that it is possible to rescue a member state and at the same time that private creditors are obliged to bear a part of the costs.
This view was interpreted as anti-European, as it accelerated the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, although in a slightly moderated form, was approved, and in the coming months we should follow the Union’s reform process, which should enable these measures from 2013.
Germany has a red line that it does not want to cross.
And he tells all of us that although measures must now be taken with which he apparently disagrees very much, from this date the old functioning of the euro will end.
The year 2013 will mark the birth of a new monetary zone, in which countries breaking the rules will be severely sanctioned and may be forced to announce payment delays, and the private sector will also have to bear a part of the costs.
Germany suggests that we must follow a strict path of growth with increased savings and investment, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and capital reserves.
They simply do not intend to tolerate another option based on receivables and building up, with the enormous gaps in the balance of payments that ruled in the years of Spain’s growth boom.
The offer is clear.
