Provoking yellow cards under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos of football, that is, rules that are not written but followed.
Part of the discussion in this case arose due to the fact that its participant was the Real Madrid team (which boasts nobleness and honor in its anthem, and which has already punished its players for similar acts), and apparently also due to the dramatization led by Mourinho, who thus adds another episode to his long history of comedian and provocator.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behavior, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether these acts circumvent the law; in fact, these are actions respecting the rules of sport, whose meaning, however, seems to try to circumvent.
The question is what kind of harm such actions cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the properties of sporting behavior is the physical inviolability of the opponents, which was not violated in these cases, i.e. there was no violent game.
Another of these characteristic features of pure play is to avoid allowing players to have an advantage over the opponent’s team due to their offence – which also did not occur here.
Therefore, the paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is the fact that there was not what we normally characterize as lust or circumvention of the law, there was not a hidden violation of the rules in order to avoid a sanction, but this behavior should be as obvious as possible in order to receive a penalty.
They loved and loved the punishment.
Another question, however, is what advantage the culprits of their deliberate transgression will have.
Here it is necessary to conclude that the opponent does not get into a disadvantaged position, and that in the current match does not get any benefit, because the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And even this is not a useful strategy for the next game, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage obviously lies in the fact that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards, which could jeopardize their participation in the future match.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, i.e. at first glance, the team can be eliminated, and in addition, by this action, the players will get rid of the penalty, and go to the second round of cards, in which to exclude is enough one card less than in the first round.
So as the wheels continue, it will not be entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, these negotiations do not go against the sporting spirit of making strategic decisions that will allow you to get the maximum benefit within the rules.
In the cases discussed here, the players did not aim to avoid punishment (which would be a clear case of circumvention), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding punishment or escaping it.
Although the boundary between cleverness and circumvention is not quite clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly cleverness.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because there were two self-exclusions and because of the way in which instructions were transmitted to provoke them from the leadership.
Damage to sports principles by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
