U.S. changes visa rules
People will have to contact the Visa Applicants Service Center before interviewing the Consular Department; costs will be lower and waiting times will be shortened.
As of January 10, 2011, the process of negotiating visas for the U.S. Embassy and consulates will change.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Visa Applicant Services (ASC) before interviewing at the Consular Department.
The ASC staff will collect the applicant’s biometric information and it will be evaluated by the Consular Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, which include:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, there will no longer be a fee for arranging a meeting, the second for processing the application and another for delivering the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee covering all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: an amount equivalent to $140 per tourist visa, $150 for visa cases with application (including visa for temporary workers) and $390 per visa for businessmen and investors.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to undergo an interview with a consular official, but will only contact the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Since biometric information will be collected at the ASC, applicants who will require a second meeting with an interview at the Consular Department will spend shorter time here than in the past.
Likewise, those who will apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra service fee of $26.
For more information about the new visa application procedure, visit the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
