The National Aviation and Space Administration (NASA) of the United States will announce tomorrow, Thursday, an astrobiological discovery that could confirm the theory of the existence of extraterrestrial life.
The discovery will be presented tomorrow at 13 a.m. by experts in astrobiology, a science that studies the origin, evolution, spread and future of life in space, at a press conference at NASA headquarters in Washington.
When inviting journalists, NASA assured that it would present “a discovery that will cause a breakthrough in the search for extraterrestrial life,” sparking speculation from experts from other countries.
The discovery could confirm the theory that there are other creatures besides us, living in hostile conditions that were considered uninhabitable, and which could represent the possibility that they will one day become intelligent creatures like humans if the conditions in which they live improve.
It appears to be a microbe found on the bottom of Lake Mono in Yosemite National Park, California, where it lives in an environment that was considered too poisonous for any form of life, as the lake is rich in arsenic.
In some ways, the creature uses arsenic for life, and this ability increases the likelihood that similar life could exist on other planets that do not have an atmosphere like Earth.
According to astrobiologists, if these organisms use arsenic in their metabolism, it will be proven that "there is another, other form of life, different from the one we know."
The space agency will announce the actual scope of the discoveries at a press conference tomorrow.
The conference will be attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who studies the possibility of life on Mars; biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists exploring Titan (Saturn’s largest moon) with the prospect that its chemical composition is similar to that of Earth.
