Global Plan for the Restoration of Lighting
The United Nations has proposed a plan to restore home lighting, store lighting and industrial spaces in 100 countries to greenhouse gas emissions reduction (GES), which is equivalent to one-third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the planet’s climate from now until 2020.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of large-scale concrete projects that the UN wants to push forward in Cancún to compensate for the lack of hard-to-realize reduction commitments on the part of industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if we replace the incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market, with fluorocompact bulbs or, even better, electroluminescent diode bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), a substantial amount of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GES emissions on the planet generated by lighting would disintegrate.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That’s equivalent to 70% of the world’s car fleet’s emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major countries with a significant share of emissions such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, joined voluntary reduction plans that should enable the reduction of global GES emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But another 5 Gt will need to be deducted from this balance sheet in order to a stabilization of global warming to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 to prevent it from getting out of control.
In heated bulbs, 95% of the energy is dispersed in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, is a product of light.
With fluorescent compact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new LED bulbs, we reduce this consumption by twice.
A fluorescent light bulb can last between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
New LED bulbs, such as those introduced by Philips this week – this company allegedly participated in a U.N. study – have an estimated life span of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a heated bulb, giving us an idea of potential savings with a replacement plan that would be applied in 100 countries.
All these new bulbs can also work with reostates and emit less heat.
They do not contain mercury.
Several experts have expressed concerns about fluorescent compact bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be classified as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries unless manufacturers set up collection plants.
However, as the report states, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not fluorocompact bulbs, but rather coal-fired power plants, which emit a lot of mercury needed to produce electricity wasted in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants put 25,000 tons of mercury into circulation a year.
The report also outlines in detail the profits each country would make from this international program.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year on electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, which is equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants, the construction of which would cost $2.5 billion.
