Hackers and Intelligent Intelligence
The case of Wikileaks has a double significance.
On the one hand, an obvious scandal is revealed, a scandal that appears to be a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it speaks of profound changes at the international level, and predicts a future controlled by regression.
Let us proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks, that is, the confirmation of the fact that every document compiled by the secret service (any nation) consists exclusively of press cuts.
The "extraordinary revelations" of Americans about Berlusconi's way of sexual life are what everyone could have read in any newspaper for months (all except Berlusconi's own), and Gaddafi's cartoon profile has long been the subject of sketches for cabaret artists.
The rule that secret documents may only consist of reports already known is crucial in the dynamics of the intelligence services, and not only in this century.
When you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric literature, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Masons) exactly what has already been written in the previous works.
And not only because the author of occult texts does not like to search for new information (not even knowing where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who practice occultism believe only what they already know and what confirms what they have already learned.
This is the success mechanism of Dan Brown.
The same applies to secret documents.
The informant is a lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) head of the intelligence services (and if not, he might, as I know, be the editor of the Libération newspaper) who considers only what he himself confesses to be true.
The highly classified information about Berlusconi, which the U.S. Embassy sent to the State Department, was the same that Newsweek published a week earlier.
So why was there so much whisper about the disclosure of these documents?
On the one hand, they say what every cultivated person already knows, namely, that embassy, at least since the end of World War II, and since heads of state can make phone calls or fly away for a dinner together, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises in representation, have transformed into spy centers.
Anyone watching films about the investigation knows very well that it is only by hypocrisy that it seems to be ignored.
However, the fact that this is repeated publicly dishonors the duty of hypocrisy and throws that bad light on American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker can obtain the most strictly classified information of the world’s most powerful country represents a tough, not negligible, blow to the prestige of this state department.
The scandal affects both the victims and its "executors".
But let’s move from here to the deep truth about what happened.
Once, in Orwell’s time, it was possible to hold all power, like some Big Brother, who controlled every movement of his people.
Orwell’s prophecy has been proven since the ability to control every movement thanks to the phone, every transaction carried out, every hotel visited, the highway used, and so on, has made the citizen a complete victim of the crown of power.
But when we demonstrate, as it is now, that even the "tombs" with the most secret information of the powerful cannot resist the intervention of any hacker, the control message ceases to be one-way and becomes a circular.
Power is controlled by every citizen, but every citizen, or at least a hacker – elected as a citizen’s avenger – can know all the secrets of power.
How can one maintain a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets?
It is true that Georg Simmel has already said that the true secret is an obscurant secret (and the obscurant secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all information about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed a mysterious obscurant secret because it is drawn from public life; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were obscurant secrets, is to deprive him of all power.
WikiLeaks did not make a mistake with Sarkozy or Merkel, but did something great with Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound of such a great power?
Obviously, in the future, states will not be able to send sensitive information online – this would be equivalent to publishing it on a poster carved on a street corner.
But it’s also quite obvious that with current technologies it’s futile to hope that it can be kept confidential messages on the phone.
There is nothing easier than to find out if and when the head of state travelled by plane and connected with any of his colleagues.
How will private and sensitive messages be kept confidential in the future?
I know well that for now my forecast is science fiction and is therefore fantastic, but I have to imagine government officials who are transported discreetly fulfilling formalities on uncontrollable routes and carrying with them only those messages that they know in memory or rather hide rare information in the heels of their shoes.
The information will be kept in unique copies in key-closed drawers: overall, the attempt to spy on the Watergate affair was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving side-by-side, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph meant a revolution in communications, the Internet rehabilitated the wireless telegraph (telephone).
Video cassettes (analog) have allowed movie lovers to shoot the movie step by step, shift it forward and back and uncover all the secrets of assembly, while now CDs (numerical) only allow you to jump through chapters, that is, through macro portions.
Through high-speed trains we get from Rome to Milan in three hours, while to travel by plane and transportation, which involves we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is not unusual that politics and communication techniques return to horseback cars.
The Last Note.
Another time, the press tried to understand what was hidden in the secrets of the embassy.
Now it’s the embassies that are asking for confidential information from the press.
Climate: How France Hacked Its Financing Promises
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to test the promise of rapidly unblocked financing (so-called fast-start or early-start financing) implemented by developed countries.
And the big French hacks were revealed
In the Copenhagen Agreement, the developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (that is, €420 million per year).
At the launch of COP16, the EU drew a big ass to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast-start financing: a report outlining the actions of its Member States, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
A transparent operation invaluable and rewarded for its true value: developed countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to do them equally and with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announces that it mobilized €2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on the right track to fulfill its promise of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on the detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
These funds are “new and additional” under the Copenhagen Agreement to ensure that the increased burden is implemented without prejudice to Public Development Aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus in what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as the year of reference: international funding has beenined and it is adding 150 million for three years to the fast-start funding title.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment dates or with dates at the level of public development aid.
In contrast, France considers the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of Public Development Aid.
Specifically, the total amount of France’s support to developing countries may remain unchanged (or even decrease) in order to meet its commitment to fund “new and additional...
Another crucial element is the division into donations and loans.
There is no rule yet and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that 1 euro borrowed is equal to 1 euro donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to prove: effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be demonstrated for certain investments that are profitable (often emission reduction projects, consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro we receive as the equivalent of one euro we give... we should not understand it from the title of our commitments, but as the price of the loan for the lender country (i.e. the equivalent of interest rate).
But France can only submit such a reasoning: it “complies” with its commitment of 420 million euros, of which 91,5% is made by loan (389.8 million euros) and 8,5% by donations (36.1 million euros) – see the EU document to verify it yourself.
It is the only country in the world that uses this type of loan.
Germany has demanded 46% from there, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) are fulfilling their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the overwhelming majority of the European Union will give 1 euro to fulfill their promise, France will give only 10 centimeters and consider this effort comparable.
A beautiful piece!
To summarize, in its “fast start” financing, France operates with a double scam: on the one hand, with the development of the stock in time and on the other, with a real financial burden.
Despite spending only €36.1 million, he is able to convince that he is spending €420 million "new and additional" in connection with his promises.
The manipulation of the finance minister (because it seems that although it is Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would member states continue to donate when it is enough to only borrow?) and in negotiations because developing countries are not entirely naive...
The early funding chapter is just a small question, relatively short-term, in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Hopefully this is not our case.
Whatever it is, it is essential to draw insights from this first year of early funding.
First, France should announce a change in its way of keeping accounts for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its obligations and of decency and fairness towards other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid discussions about deposits in long-term financing (another key chapter currently being discussed): we do not escape the question of "additionality" or how to account for loans.
France should change its stance to become as progressive with these deposits as it is with others.
Therefore, everyone puts hope in the new environment minister, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will visit Cancun next week.
The surprising announcement of France’s fast-start and its vision of “additionality” and the use of loans could raise the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in the discussions.
A warning about pesticides that children will consume.
A ten-year-old child consumes 81 different chemicals one day, according to one study published this Wednesday, from the Association of Future Generations (ex-Rights and Preservation Movement for Future Generations).
The association, which points out that its results “do not have a significant statistical value given the low number of analysed samples, but are characteristic of the problem being processed,” bought between July and September foods commonly consumed in four meals and one light meal as a snack for one child about a decade old in supermarkets in l’Oise and Paris.
These typical meals, including official recommendations – five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day – as well as candy, have been analyzed by research laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are ranked as carcinogens, possible or likely, and five are among the clear carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that could act as interfering for glands with internal discharge (PE), according to studies by several institutions, such as the International Centre for Research on Cancer.
"Al in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, in our research we see well that the reality in consumer exposure to contaminants, potentially carcinogenic, and/or PE is striking," the association said.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea contain about ten residues with potential carcinogenic effects and three proven certain carcinogens, as is the case for about twenty residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, which was by studies as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, included in the lunch, in which studies have discovered traces of potent insecticides banned in the EU.
Furthermore, the steak from the milled meat, the tuna in the can, and even the goose and chewing gum were rubbed with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water, analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
A steak of salmon for dinner was "the richest" with 34 chemical residues discovered, and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat food in the microwave did not avoid the analysis.
The ultimate risk to consumers of this “cocktail of contaminants” is probably underestimated,” the study finds.
Green Europe-Greens (EE-LV) has proposed a moratorium on the use of pesticides "in the face of an emergency" to stop the "rise of civilizational diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) examined the residual status of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
